                        Biography = "Lyuben Stoychev Karavelov (c. 1834 – January 21, 1879) was a Bulgarian writer, journalist, publicist, and revolutionary, and one of the key figures of the Bulgarian National Revival. He was born in the town of Koprivshtitsa in a family of craftsmen and merchants and received his early education in local schools before continuing his studies in Plovdiv and abroad. In the 1860s he lived in Serbia, Hungary, and Russia, where he became involved with the ideas of Slavic mutuality and the broader European revolutionary movements of the time. Karavelov eventually settled in Bucharest, which became a major center of Bulgarian émigré political and cultural activity. There he edited and published influential newspapers such as Svoboda (Freedom) and Nezavisimost (Independence), which argued for democratic ideals, national liberation, and social reform and helped form public opinion among Bulgarians under Ottoman rule. As a writer, he produced short stories, novellas, travelogues, and publicistic works that depicted Bulgarian life with realism, humor, and a strong moral and patriotic tone; among his best-known literary works are the stories Bulgarian Old Times and Hadji Nicho, which vividly portray the world of the Bulgarian town and merchant class on the eve of liberation. Karavelov was also one of the founders and early leaders of the Bulgarian Revolutionary Central Committee (BRCC) and initially worked closely with revolutionaries such as Vasil Levski, contributing to the organizational and ideological preparation for a nationwide uprising. In his later years he became more cautious and favored constitutional and evolutionary paths to national freedom, which led to tensions with more radical figures. He died in Ruse on January 21, 1879, shortly after the Liberation of Bulgaria, leaving a lasting legacy as both a classic writer and a major intellectual architect of the national liberation movement.",
